{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17567758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17567758"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:07:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19325"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19325"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.22,0.03,0.6,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12059"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83069"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12059"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68134"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"422"},{"type":"tags","id":"687"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2356"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28421"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28422"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28427"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83069"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to a rural Emergency Department after intentionally ingesting paraquat herbicide 30 minutes ago. His wife found him in the shed with an empty bottle of paraquat and brought him immediately to hospital. His clothes and skin are visibly contaminated with green herbicide liquid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has severe oral pain and ulceration. His chest is clear to auscultation. His abdomen is soft but tender in the epigastrium.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate safety measure for healthcare workers?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Standard precautions (gloves and hand hygiene only)","Contact precautions, including gown and gloves","Airborne precautions with N95 mask","Full PPE including gloves, gown, eye protection, and mask","Immediate decontamination of the patient\u0027s skin but no PPE is required"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen managing patients contaminated with paraquat, healthcare worker safety is paramount. Paraquat can be absorbed through intact skin and mucous membranes, making proper protection essential. \u003Cstrong\u003EFull PPE including gloves, gown, eye protection, and mask\u003C/strong\u003E is required to prevent secondary exposure to healthcare workers during initial assessment and decontamination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStandard precautions\u003C/strong\u003E with gloves alone are inadequate given the risk of splash exposure and skin contact with the chemical. The visible contamination of the patient\u0027s clothes and skin indicates a high risk of secondary exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContact precautions\u003C/strong\u003E with gown and gloves provide insufficient protection as they do not protect the face and eyes from potential splash exposure during decontamination or if the patient vomits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAirborne precautions with N95 mask\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not provide adequate protection against skin and mucous membrane exposure. While respiratory protection is important, comprehensive barrier protection is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate decontamination without PPE\u003C/strong\u003E would put healthcare workers at risk of exposure. While decontamination is essential, it must be performed while wearing appropriate PPE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter ensuring staff safety with appropriate PPE, the patient should be decontaminated, including removal of contaminated clothing and washing of affected skin. All contaminated materials should be treated as hazardous waste.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Full personal protective equipment (PPE) is required when managing patients contaminated with paraquat to prevent secondary exposure.","Paraquat can be absorbed through intact skin and mucous membranes, making decontamination and barrier protection essential.","Healthcare worker safety is paramount when managing chemical exposures, requiring appropriate PPE before patient contact."],"references":["Gawarammana, et al. Medical management of paraquat ingestion. Br J Clin Pharmacol. 2011. https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3243009/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68134"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19325"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68134"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-01T22:35:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T23:34:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12059"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83069"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups"